  "signature": "ed25519:9b1e3f7a2c4d6e8f0a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FDA-cleared FEA software (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) with documented QA procedures including regression test suite, version control under 21 CFR Part 11-compliant configuration management, and NIST-traceable benchmark verification. Achieved level 3 requires documented software validation plan and passing benchmark suite.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is operated under a documented software quality assurance plan consistent with FDA guidance on software as a medical device. Configuration management logs, regression test results, and installation qualification records were reviewed. All benchmarks passed within tolerance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification at level 3 requires demonstration via manufactured-solution or benchmark tests that solver implementation is consistent with governing equations. At least two independent benchmark problems spanning the relevant physics (contact, large deformation, elasto-plasticity) must pass with error norms below 1%.",
      "rationale": "Code verification benchmarks for nonlinear contact and elasto-plastic material response were executed and documented in the project verification report. Manufactured-solution tests confirmed spatial convergence consistent with second-order accuracy. All error norms satisfied the <1% threshold."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires a formal mesh convergence study across at least three element densities with Richardson extrapolation or equivalent, demonstrating QoI discretization error below 5% relative to the extrapolated solution.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the pedicle screw–vertebral body interface region. Richardson extrapolation yielded a discretization error estimate of 2.1% for stiffness and 3.4% for yield force. The production mesh (approximately 480,000 elements) was selected at the knee of the convergence curve."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires documented solver convergence criteria (force and displacement residuals) and demonstration that solution is insensitive to solver tolerance settings over at least one order of magnitude.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson convergence was monitored with force residual tolerance 1e-4 and displacement residual tolerance 1e-5. A tolerance sensitivity study confirmed QoI variation below 0.3% when tightening tolerances by one order of magnitude."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 2 requires documented model setup procedures, independent analyst review of boundary condition application, and sign-off by a qualified simulation engineer.",
      "rationale": "Model setup was performed by one analyst and independently reviewed by a second analyst with equivalent qualifications. Boundary conditions, load application points, and contact pair definitions were verified against the ASTM F1717 test fixture drawings. No discrepancies were identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires documented justification that the selected constitutive models (material, contact) are appropriate for the loading regime and that at least one sensitivity analysis has been performed on key model-form assumptions.",
      "rationale": "A bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model was selected for the titanium alloy screw based on published Ti-6Al-4V monotonic stress-strain data. Sensitivity to tangent modulus (±20%) produced less than 4% variation in yield force QoI. Frictional contact (μ=0.3) was justified by literature values for Ti–UHMWPE interfaces."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires that all material and geometric inputs are traceable to NIST-traceable measurements or certified material certificates, with uncertainty bounds documented for each key input parameter.",
      "rationale": "Screw geometry was derived from coordinate-measuring machine (CMM) measurements traceable to NIST standards. Material properties were obtained from certified mill test reports for the Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used to manufacture the test specimens. Uncertainty bounds for elastic modulus (±2 GPa) and yield strength (±15 MPa) were propagated through a Monte Carlo analysis."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires N≥10 test specimens from production-representative manufacturing lots with documented dimensional inspection confirming conformance to design nominal within drawing tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens were drawn from a single production lot. Dimensional inspection confirmed all critical dimensions within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Lot traceability documentation was archived."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The validation testing was conducted strictly in accordance with ASTM F1717 under a single standardized test condition (6° offset angle, 10 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature 23±2°C, UHMWPE block fixture). The protocol was executed identically at both participating laboratories, and inter-laboratory reproducibility was confirmed by comparing mean QoI values (coefficient of variation across labs <4% for all three QoIs). Environmental controls were monitored continuously and logged. However, only a single set of test conditions was employed: no variation in offset angle, loading rate, or temperature was explored. ASME V&V 40 level 3 for Test conditions requires that the validation domain span at least two distinct parametric conditions relevant to the COU envelope, enabling assessment of model predictive capability across the anticipated operating range. Because the COU is defined for a single ASTM F1717 configuration and the regulatory submission does not require demonstration of model fidelity across varied loading rates or temperatures, the project team made a deliberate scope decision to test at one condition only. This decision was reviewed and accepted by the credibility assessment team lead. The resulting achieved level of 2 is noted as a gap relative to the required level of 3; risk is partially mitigated by the high inter-laboratory reproducibility and by the fact that the ASTM F1717 protocol itself fully defines the intended use condition. A formal gap disposition is recorded in the project risk register (Risk ID: SIM-2023-007)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires documented traceability between each experimental input parameter (geometry, material, boundary conditions, loading) and the corresponding FEA model input, with quantified differences and uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency matrix was constructed mapping each of 14 experimental input parameters to its FEA counterpart. Maximum geometric deviation was 0.03 mm (screw thread root radius); maximum material property deviation was 1.8% (elastic modulus). All deviations were within the uncertainty bounds propagated in the model inputs assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires quantitative comparison of all QoIs using a validation metric that accounts for experimental uncertainty (e.g., E/uval), with a pre-specified pass/fail threshold documented prior to analysis.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval was computed for stiffness (0.87), yield force (1.12), and force at 40 mm (1.04). All values are below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96 (95% confidence interval criterion). The <10% QoI difference criterion was also satisfied for all three quantities. Metric thresholds were documented in the validation plan dated 2023-03-15, prior to unblinding experimental data."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires documented justification that the selected QoIs are directly linked to the clinical risk drivers identified in the risk analysis and that the QoIs are sensitive to the failure modes of concern.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement were selected based on their direct correspondence to the three failure modes identified in the FMEA: excessive flexibility (stiffness), permanent deformation onset (yield force), and catastrophic structural failure (force at 40 mm). Sensitivity analysis confirmed that all three QoIs respond monotonically to the dominant uncertainty sources."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Level 3 requires that the validation scenario matches the COU in all critical dimensions (geometry, loading, boundary conditions, material) and that any differences are documented and shown to be conservative or negligible.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity replicates the COU exactly: same screw geometry, same ASTM F1717 fixture, same loading protocol, same material lot. No surrogate geometry or scaled model was employed. The validation is therefore direct rather than extrapolated, satisfying the highest relevance criterion for the factors assessed."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single gap (Test conditions, achieved 2 vs. required 3) is formally documented in the project risk register and accepted on the basis that ASTM F1717 defines a single normative test configuration consistent with the COU, inter-laboratory reproducibility is high (CV<4%), and the regulatory submission scope does not require multi-condition validation. Overall credibility is judged sufficient for a Medium model risk, Medium assurance level determination. The assessment package is accepted.",
